I‚Äôm absolutely obsessed with my new products from @zenish.ca ‚ú® Zenish is an amazing new company started by @meerajah & @tayalexras ‚Äî these girls get that wellness is something that SO many of us struggle with incorporating into our daily lives. It does not have to be an all or nothing: if you‚Äôre not able to wake up for 6am yoga & drink a green smoothie daily, then all hope isn‚Äôt lost for you. Zenish‚Äôs products are designed to help you incorporate a small bit of ~zen~ into your life, whenever you have the time. First: are the howlite, amazonite & rose quartz bracelets. These bracelets are all made with ethically sourced stones & infused with reiki energy to help reduce stress and anxiety throughout the day. As someone who admittedly has a LOT of stress and anxieties some days, these bracelets are a great way for me to incorporate wellness into my entire day. Next: is the satin eye pillow in this super cute limited edition tie dye print. Infused with lavender & reiki energy, not only does this also reduce stress and anxiety, but it can be warmed in the microwave and used to help treat head and neck aches. This is the season for letting go. Making room for what is new, and opportunities to grow. - MHN ü§çAh, opportunities to grow! There may be times in life that we are not able to grow because of certain things in our life that is holding us back. Yes, i said it - things that ARE holding us back. These things can be baggages in our lives. Things like a past relationship, toxic friendships, bad attitudes, bad behaviors, things you have done in the past that you are not able to let go and God is saying ‚Äúhey, I have forgiven you but you need to LET GO!‚Äù. Trust me, I have been there and it‚Äôs not easy. But the more i have thought about on where I could have been and where God wanted to place me instead of thinking about my past season the more it made me realize how much i needed to LET GO and LET GOD! ‚ú®So here‚Äôs a question for you today: Are you ready to let go and let God transform your life, take you to another level?

God is not in a hurry. You are. It‚Äôs why you are tired. It‚Äôs why you are anxious, stressed and disappointed. Today, I pray that you surrender your timeline in favor of His peace. With covid-19, protests and riots, shutdowns, quarantine, deaths, divorce rates gone up and finally the Presidential Election! 2020 has been NUTS! But has Go. stopped taking care of His people? Has God stopped moving? Has God forgotten about his people? It‚Äôs simple, NO. God is still in control and still on the throne. My prayer today is that you may know that God loves you deeply. However 2020 may end, know that the Lord is taking care of every detail of your life...REST! ü§ç

I call this look ‚Äúmuppet chic‚Äù ü§£‚ùÑÔ∏è Would you believe we shot this photo at night!? I asked Reuben to share 3 tips for shooting bright photos at night and here they areüì∏üëá (save this post so you can reference them on your next photoshoot) 1.) Use a speed-light/flash, Reuben recommends not pointing the flash directly at the subject and bouncing the light off of something else for a more ‚Äúnatural‚Äù shot. This is his secret to using the flash but not having the shots look like we used it. 2.) Use the lowest F-stop to open up the Aperture of the image as much as possible. This will let more light into the image without compromising quality. 3.) If your subject is stationary, utilize a tripod and a very low shutter speed to let addition light in the image. 4.) If you want additional light (brightness) in your images after doing all of the above, Reu recommends turning up iso, which will let even more light into your image, however try not to go over 800 with your Iso as a very high iso can reduce the quality of your image. Like this post for more tips! üì∏ wearing @kariberryposh

column2: This has been a crazy time for health care workers. I know it‚Äôs not a lot, but there are three Heath care professionals that I owe a huge ‚ÄúThank You‚Äù to. Without them, my life would be very different. First, Dr. Thomason, my liver doctor from 2007. He saved my life! Thank You so much! I wasn‚Äôt 100% coherent all the times we talked, but you took the time to explain, run tests, and monitor me on a daily basis. Second, my kids Pediatrician, Dr. Kathy O‚Äômara. Because of her knowledge and fast acting decisions, we were comforted when Alexis was in the hospital at 9 days old. It was also thanks to her and her keen awareness that we jumped on the ball to have Logan tested for autism at such a critical age. Third, and most recent, Dr Steve Taylor, my ENT/Surgeon. A HUGE thank you to him for realizing right away that it was my airway and not Asthma or Allergies, that was making it so I couldn‚Äôt breathe.

The December 1st Box is one of my favorite traditions. Instead of waiting until Christmas Eve to open their Christmas Pajamas, we now give our kids their Christmas PJ‚Äôs on December 1st with a few other fun Christmas themed items. That way, they can use them all month! üéÑ..
On this last day of November, I‚Äôm so grateful for a job that I love! Who would have thought that my hobby would turn into (almost) a full time job?

Today I am so very grateful for the Carmen B. Pingree School of Autism. The school, Logan‚Äôs Pre-School Teachers, home tutors, and Carmen and John Pingree (who we had the opportunity go to dinner with) all hold a special place in my heart. They brought such understanding, love, and peace to us in a time of absolute uncertainty. I‚Äôve always said, if I ever win the lottery, my first check will be to them, as a way to repay them for all the support and love they showed us. Logan wouldn‚Äôt be where he is today without them! ‚ù§Ô∏è

column3: #sponsored‚Ä¢We grew lots of veggies this year, zucchini, peppers, tomatoes, collards, cabbage, peas, onions, and leeks to name a few! We don‚Äôt have to let it go to waste! @BonniePlants and @AmpleHarvest teamed up to help local food pantries take in food from home gardeners. column2: Did anyone else plant a quarantine garden? üôã‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è I‚Äôve been wanting to plant a vegetable garden for years, but until this year, it really wasn‚Äôt a priority. column3: #sponsored‚Ä¢We ended up planting more than we could eat. And during this time where so many local families are hurting, it felt wrong to throw away perfectly good food. @BonniePlants joined forces with @AmpleHarvest to help make an impact on our neighbors and our communities. Now, you can DONATE your home grown vegetables to the hungry in your community. Talk about a game changer! Head over to AmpleHarvest.org, and see where you can donate near you! #bonniegrowsmore

Before I go into hibernation mode before the holidays, let‚Äôs take a moment to flashback a few weeks to my visit to Chalk Hill Estates. I‚Äôve enjoyed their wine and virtual events before but had yet to visit the winery in person. I have to say, it was stunning. The safe and socially distant experience they set up for @capturedhappiness_photography and me was picturesque and set in what used to be their equestrian center. We ate guava/pineapples grown on their property, we tasted some pretty exquisite wines, we toured the extensive grounds, and we shot A LOT of fun photos. Thanks for having us @chalkhillestate and thanks for making us feel so comfortable and safe during these crazy times. Photos by @capturedhappiness_photography //
There is magic in the air. It still lives there. The air is thick with worry but if you squint through the fog, the magic still lives there. Swipe to see Lennon‚Äôs first Tahoe snowfall 2 years ago.

4 days in the snow, 7 pieces, apres ski look success.Snow suit by @topshop via @nordstrom Base layers by @sweatybetty via @nordstrom Snow boots by @pajarcanada Hiking boots by @toms Statement turtleneck by Stella Macartney by @adidaswomen Fleece lined leggings by @90degreebyreflex Sunglasses by @rayban Gaitor via @amazoninfluencerprogram

I spent 4 days with my pandemic pod in a house in South Lake Tahoe. After 10+ months without travel and a very limited lifestyle, it was so nice to get my parents out into nature and the fresh mountain air. Lennon and Nico experienced the snow, Lennon conquered the art of sledding and I learned to make homemade chili and lasagna. We are ready to head back home and lay low for the next few weeks but feeling very full and blessed we had these moments outdoors and in nature.
How it started vs. how it‚Äôs going. Two year old sledding edition.
Kindness is like snow - It beautifies everything it covers. ‚Äî Kahlil Gibran

Being in the mountains reminds me of growing up in the Pacific Northwest and spending the winters at my uncle‚Äôs log cabin. Snow fights, snow mobiles, forts, hot chocolate, cutting down our own tree, waiting up for Santa. It‚Äôs a childhood experience that I was worried I wouldn‚Äôt be able to pass on to Lennon. This year we snuck away for a week to the mountains to try and recreate some magic. Being away from the TV, the news, and the anxiety of simple errands has been therapeutic. We found snow, we cooked chili, we went on a hike. Today we wrote our letters to Santa and made snowflakes for the tree at home. It‚Äôs too bad it took me a 3 hour drive to get outside my own head for a while but there is no better place to do it then in the gorgeous Sierras. //
Adventure on my love. Adventure on. //
Headed up to the mountains for a little escape and looking back at some of my favorite Tahoe winter looks. Any one else love getting comfy cozy?

And off to the mountains we go. I‚Äôve been needing an adventure for a few months now and have been trying to plan a safe local escape with Lennon. I also promised to show her the snow this year so it is official, off to the mountains we go.

Long post alert! My‚ù§Ô∏èTHANKS YOU! I appreciate every single one of you here. Every like, comment, story view, response to my stories, DMs and shopping through my links ‚Äì I appreciate every single action you take on my account. Your support is why I‚Äôm here, and I‚Äôm beyond grateful. I often wonder about how other bloggers, Instagrammers, influencers, content creators, etc. got started, so I thought I‚Äôd share a little of my story today ‚ù§Ô∏è I‚Äôll start by saying that this account is still very small in comparison to many other bloggers and Instagrammers that you follow, and it‚Äôs taken me a LONG TIME ‚Äì like 3 years ‚Äì to get to where I am now. I‚Äôm not an expert, and I don‚Äôt have an overnight success story to share. As I‚Äôve mentioned before, this account is a passion project of mine. It‚Äôs not how I make a living - although yes, it is monetized. When I graduated college, social media wasn‚Äôt even a thing! You guys, Facebook was around for a good ten years before I even joined ‚Äì can you say late to the social media party?!? Even though affordable fashion and everyday style have ALWAYS been interests of mine, I never imagined I‚Äôd be posting outfit inspiration because this wasn‚Äôt even a thing when I was thinking about a career. But, evolution is fun and keeps our lives interesting! Some of you may remember that a few years ago, I had a small business that sold women‚Äôs scarves and other accessories. I received lots of questions about the outfits that I styled with my scarves, so I thought I‚Äôd create an account that shared my outfits and provided style inspiration. That‚Äôs it üëèüèª To those of you who are thinking about sharing a passion of yours and are thinking about where to start, just start! There is no perfect way to do it and no perfect time to begin. I don‚Äôt have any fancy equipment or a professional photographer behind the lens. All of my photos are taken with an iphone by my husband (who has zero photography training, lol). If I could share a few tips, it would be to believe in yourself, bring value to your followers, be consistent in what you post, post regularly and HAVE FUN! XOXO

column3: #DryTortugas National Park is one of the most unique eco attraction located on the secluded Garden Key which is ~ 70 miles away from Key West and situated in the Gulf of Mexico. It is the largest brick masonry structure in America. You can only access it by ferry, private charter or seaplane. Only 1% of it is land (99% water) and it also features a 19th century fort, named after Thomas Jefferson. Fort Jefferson was built in 1846 and was once used as a prison in the civil war. ‚Å£‚Å£If you are a history buff this place is for you! Also ideal for snorkeling, especially if you never have. I personally wouldn‚Äôt return because I think it is overpriced - almost $200 PER PERSON! Imagine my face when I found out getting here via seaplane was double the cost of the ferry lol although probably a much cooler experience + more time on the island. Overall, I was satisfied to check this experience off my bucketlist‚úîÔ∏è. The tour did include a small breakfast (bagel, apple, juice and yogurt), lunch (Turkey or ham sandwich, some snacks, and water/soft drink), snorkeling gear, optional fully narrated 45 minute tour, entrance fee and of course the round trip ferry ride (I believe Yankee Freedom III is currently the only company who provides this tour). Their service was satisfactory. Alcoholic beverages are provided at an additional cost. We also had to pay $30 for parking at the meeting point. ‚Å£‚Å£It would have been more worth it to me had we camped out there for at least a night but the campsite was sold out all the way till May/June!! üòÖ‚Å£In conclusion, if you can afford it, I say go at least once in your life because it‚Äôs definitely unique. A hidden gem in the USA. The views are UNBEATABLE, UNREAL and UNMATCHED (check stories/Key West highlights). ‚Å£‚Å£Is #DryTortugasNationalPark on your bucket list? Had you ever heard of this place prior to now? ‚Å£‚Å£#ProTip BRING BIODEGRADABLE BUG REPELLENT AND SUNSCREEN!‚Å£

column3: #ChallengeAccepted‚úîÔ∏è. Thanks for nominating me @irenelenoire @tjummy and @loveherculture . I would encourage you all to look deeper into the meaning of this challenge before posting a b&w photo just to be part of a trend. A little lesson for those who may not know, this movement originated from Turkey to raise awareness of the alarming rate at which women are being murdered just for simply being a woman (‚Äòfemicide‚Äô) and to highlight the fact that your face could be next to appear on the newspaper. Another issue is that the Turkish govt. has done nothing to protect women from these crimes. As a matter of fact they are trying to abolish some basic human rights which will make it LEGAL to ignore hate crimes against women in their country. This would definitely be one of those countries I‚Äôll think twice about traveling solo. ‚Å£‚Å£I stand in solidarity with the Turkish women as well as all the families who have lost a loved one due to any act of violence. ‚Å£‚Å£Women uplifting, encouraging and supporting other women and I‚Äôm forever here for it. Sending love to all the resilient, radiant and phenomenal women I know, including Sandra Bland, Breonna Taylor, Vanessa Guillen, and many more üñ§ü§ç‚Å£

column2: I‚Äôd still choose to be BLACK. Over and over again üñ§
Born tired.

Ive been wanting to spend time with Cairo all day. I decided I‚Äôd take her to the park because it‚Äôs her favorite place. It took Queen Cairo and I almost 20 minutes to get to the park. It could have taken 10 if she trusted me.Cairo loves to run and her daddy and I are always reminding her that she can‚Äôt do it on the main road in our neighborhood because it‚Äôs too busy. She‚Äôs well aware that cars can hit you but what started off as a warning has become a fear.She‚Äôll walk freely, even run, but the minute she hears or sees a car she refuses to move, even if she‚Äôs holding my hand. Our walk stretched into 20 minutes because I had to coax her into trusting that it was ok to walk with me as cars were passing by as long as she was holding my hand. I reminded her more than once that she‚Äôs my favorite girl in the world and I won‚Äôt let anything happen to her. By the time the fourth car drove pass she was repeating it ‚Äúmommy won‚Äôt let anything happen to me. Just hold mommy‚Äôs hand‚Äù and by cars six and seven she was willing to keep walking. I‚Äôm not going to lie, I was slightly annoyed. It was cold! But I gave her grace because I saw myself in her paranoia. She literally had a paralysis of analysis and refused to move! I‚Äôve been just like that recently. Like Cairo, I‚Äôm on my way to a destination I‚Äôve always wanted to visit but I keep letting fear of being hit by rejection, hit by failure, hit by success üëÄ stop me in my tracks. We can be so consumed by fear of the negative that we forget who is holding our hand. Remember that you are God‚Äôs favorite. That he will hold your hand and guide you if you let him and carry you safely to the destination he set. He‚Äôll also get you there in less time if you trust him rather than stopping every time something looks or sounds scary...üì∏ @lyndahwellsphotography ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

Or embraced it with fear?Are you sitting here wondering "where did time go?"Or standing up cheering "I made my life grow!"Did you finish those goals, accomplish those plans?Or did you make excuses rather than thinking "I can!"No matter what the year has brought forth,On December 31st don't you dare get caughtWishing, reminiscing, and feeling distraughtWhen you have the power to change your lot!The power is within you its begging escape,So put on those running shoes and fasten your cape;There is still time to do anything, even lose weightIf you put in the work and expand your faith.New business? Go get it! New body? Why not?New attitude? Its up to you, don't let your life rot!For there will come a time when we see December no moreWhen our bodies are lying beneath the earth's floor.While we are alive and well, its imperative you seeThat we use our potential to be all we can be.This month is the month of the completion, old things will move onSo  come on, get going and lets finish strong.Set new goals, set new boundaries, there's no limit for livingMake use of the gifts the creator has given.Its Christmas dear friends! And if you truly believeThat a virgin can give birth, then you can also receiveHis grace and his mercy, his strength and his might,To bring forth your vision and shine your bright light.So on this first day in the month of December You have the power in you, always remember."COPYRIGHT Anastarcia Huyler Palacious 2014

Wait‚Ä¶.sitting on the couch doom scrolling isn‚Äôt ‚Äúgood‚Äù for me? Interesting.‚Ä¢After months of election anxiety and depression about the upcoming winter, I have finally hit a wall. Turns out sitting down to work, standing in front of the fridge, and binging Bravo is not the most sustainable plan for happiness. The housewives can only do so much. The only good thing about rock bottom is I am forced to move in a positive direction (and just MOVE period).‚Ä¢Lately, I have been trying to think of ways to exercise that don‚Äôt feel like punishment. This week Eric and I did a Zumba class that kicked our BUTTS. I burned 600 calories?? I found out @classpass has tons of live Zoom classes across the country and on-demand workouts you can take whenever you want. And honestly the Zoom Zumba class we took was the most fun I‚Äôve had working out. It felt like being back in the dance studio from my younger days. She‚Äôs still got it üíÉüèº‚Ä¢I‚Äôve also taken a couple of @classpass HIIT classes and have a meditation class lined up for this week- I‚Äôm finally feeling motivated to get my body moving and out of this funk. If you want to check out their other classes I popped the link in my bio üíû‚Ä¢PS Let me know if you want us to show you some of our Zumba moves‚Ä¶Maybe after a few more classes üòò

SAVE FOR LATER üìåFind time to center yourself this Holiday seasonüôèüèæBeing still is something I struggle with. I‚Äôm a go-getter, a mover and a shaker. Being still is something I just don‚Äôt have time to do...or so I thought. Yesterday I meditated for the first time. Like truly meditated. I got lost in the quiet and the stillness. It was perfect. It was magic. Tomorrow is a day to give thanks, but it should also...if possible...be a day to be still. Relax, reflect and calm the mind. Eat the pie. Unbutton your pants. Have seconds. LIVE unapologetically my friend.When the noise settles and the dishes are done, find a quiet spot to just...breathe.Will you set aside time tomorrow to pour back into yourself with me? Thinking of you this season. Special thanks to @2020meditationllc for showing us the way.

My NYC chapter is closed. Closing my apartment door for the last time was incredibly emotional. It felt as though I was physically turning the last page of this story. I‚Äôve lived the best years of my life here. I‚Äôve loved and I‚Äôve lost, I‚Äôve formed the best friendships of my life, and I‚Äôve learned so much about myself. I‚Äôve grown from a sheltered girl to a independent, no-bullshit, sassy woman. NYC your spirit and your fight will always live on in me and it will set me apart as I open the next storyline that is my life. This isn‚Äôt goodbye, it‚Äôs I‚Äôll see you soon, NYC. Been reflecting a lot on my time in NYC and it has been the best years of my life. It is the longest I have ever lived somewhere and I am so grateful this has been my home for the past 10 years. I first came to NYC my senior year of high school during my college tour and had to stop by MTV studios (yes, I am old and it was my dream to be a @mtv VJ). I knew I would be back. I spent college summers in the city, getting completely lost and indulging in all the city has to offer a bit too much, only solidifying my desire to be here full time. I moved here after college and never thought anywhere else could be home. That made this one of the toughest decisions I‚Äôve had to make to leave but I refuse to say goodbye. There are many visits in my future, that much I know.I do wonder if my path will lead back here permanently again but until then, I‚Äôll have incredible memories to look back on. Thank you, NYC for taking in a naive girl and turning her into a strong, independent woman. üóΩ

I AM MOVING! AH, I cannot believe it. As I slowly pack and sell my furniture it is becoming more and more surreal. My time in NYC is coming to an end. I have a week left in the city and while I wish I could have celebrated the closing of this decade long chapter it just means I‚Äôll have to come back when it‚Äôs safer to have my going away party! There are so many places I wanted to go and people I wish I could see, hug and drunkenly tumble out of bars with but we‚Äôll make up for lost time soon, friends. Until then, I‚Äôm only a DM, a text or a FaceTime away. üóΩ‚úàÔ∏èüåÅPC: @newyorkcity

2 days until we know what Baby Schafer will be. I cannot even handle it! This is better than being a kid on Christmas Eve waiting for Santa to come!Here‚Äôs what we‚Äôve decided. We‚Äôre staying in our own new parent bubble and soaking up every moment of goodness. Not to say things aren‚Äôt going to be hard becoming parents but the amount of unsolicited advice and even when you look up new parent quotes, it‚Äôs gloomy. Most things paint a picture of all the hard times which over shadow the good moments. Call us naive, living in our own world, too positive ... it‚Äôs where we will remain through it all. With all my health conditions I was told if I wanted kids, I needed to make it happen by 27. Being only a couple weeks away of turning 34, that alone is enough for us to be beyond thankful to our mighty God and soak up every moment of positivity. ÔøºThe months where the tests said negative and we still kept faith until we seen a positive is enough happiness to hold on to for a lifetime. So yes, while parenthood is challenging, we choose to focus on all the good instead of the challenges ahead. From one upcoming mama to another, YOU get to choose what your new journey looks like. Don‚Äôt let the hardships ahead blur the miracle and positivity happening now. üíó

Today marks the 3rd month end making the last 3 months real. If I‚Äôm being honest I don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs truly set in yet. Let me explain. In February I walked from my previous company at the top rank I was with for 6 years in the middle of a pandemic at that üôà I don‚Äôt care what anyone says, rebuilding & getting back to the top is scary. Can I do it again? Was the last time just a fluke? Do I even have it in me again? These are all thoughts people have when starting over whether they want to admit it or not. Fast forward to August, my incredible tribe of babes & I hit Platinum. With this rank comes a $30k cash bonus that is given to you in 3 payments of $10k each month you hit it. August I received a $10k cash bonus. September I received a $10k cash bonus. Now that October has officially closed out, I will receive my last $10k cash bonuse. All of this on top of my commissions, mentor bonuses, leadership pool bonuses, enroller bonuses, lifestyle bonus ... it‚Äôs honestly mind blowing to me still even typing that out. I‚Äôm kind of a superstitious person, so even though every month I could have posted I earned a $10k bonus, I wanted to make sure we crossed the finish line making it official that I can say I received the full $30k, a trip to Napa, a $5k Platinum party my CEO is throwing for me & my team & a set of Diamond earrings. üò≠ To me it was important to be able to prove not only to myself but to others that even with those doubtful thoughts I told you I had, that it IS possible to start over & flourish like you‚Äôve never before. column2: Driving this baby off the lot I cried because it hit me hard that so much of what I once prayed for is happening in my life. 2020 was a whirlwind of downs and some insanely high highs! While all the uncertainty in the world swirled around I took a risk and walked away from a business to start over, during a pandemic üò≥ Some might think it was dumb. Me on the other hand felt like I had to follow my gut and the constant nudges God was giving me to trust the path he had cleared for me. It was honestly the scariest decision I‚Äôve ever made in my life. But one thing I‚Äôve learned through my journey over the last 10 years is that the biggest rewards are always on the other side of the risks you‚Äôre terrified to take. My only regret is not doing it sooner. @jordanschafer21 reminded me today to not shrink down my accomplishments or even how hard I work. Which is hard for me. I battle constantly the feeling of why me? What did I do to deserve this? And the biggest fear of all, going back to where I started. I‚Äôm still a work in progress and little by little I let go of these fears and step into my blessings. I want to be a voice of inspiration for anyone who feels like you are stuck in a place where it‚Äôs never going to get better. Listen to me when I say it can! But it starts with you and your mind set. Even on my lowest days, somewhere I found the ability to allow myself to dream big. I need you to let yourself do that. What do you want? Now, go after it! It might not be right away, but every step you take that gets you closer to that will change your situation. I‚Äôm proof of that. And on days when you don‚Äôt believe in yourself, I do üíóHuge shout out to Hector at @landroverorlando and all their help getting this beauty over here for me. It was an honor being the first Defender 90 X sold by him. It was the longest month of my life counting down like a kid on Christmas üòÇ I couldn‚Äôt be more proud to be part of the Land Rover family.

‚ô° I am not one to take selfie‚Äôs and post them much on my feed, but this deserved a spot because I was trying out my new iPhone 12 Pro üòÇ Also, because I want to raise awareness on different body types and how YES, it‚Äôs not just about ‚Äúfat‚Äù body types that have issues. All body types do. Including myself and my overly thin frame. There needs to be awareness so that people don‚Äôt continue to tell others ‚ÄúOh you‚Äôre thin, get over it. People die to be thin.‚Äù Because it‚Äôs not about that. Body image goes ALL ways. Thin, fat, average. Whatever it is. And to be told to stop complaining because being thin is good, I‚Äôm here to tell you, it isn‚Äôt good all the time. Believe me. I have issues with how I look being thin. How clothes look on me. How lanky I look and feel. I wanna start raising awareness on this issue because I know many in my position are also being told to stop complaining. Who‚Äôs with me?! {If you haven‚Äôt seen my stories on this subject, go do so!}//

A very short version of the last months in iso. There‚Äôs been a lot more crying, animal sickness and death, and the continued struggle that comes with a battle I‚Äôll never be able to share. column2: Media and politics affects us all, yet we only see black people in political discourse when something has happened that is deemed 'black'. column3: #sponsored We need health-based solutions to the current opioid crisis. This is something that‚Äôs prevalent amongst people my age, and hits close to home for me. Be prepared, you can pick up a naloxone kit at your local Ontario pharmacy. Administrating naloxone can reverse the effects of an overdose until medical help arrives, and if used right away, it may be able to help the person breathe again. Naloxone is not a substitute for emergency medical care. Opioid related harms (or deaths) can be avoided, and it takes little to no effort to be a part of a naloxone ready community @fightthecrisis. #fightthecrisis #betheone #naloxone

column2: Yesterday was a rough, I mean rough day! From bad news, to just one of those days where everything is going wrong. Today will hopefully be much better & to raise my spirits I am thinking of our trip to Cape May last weekend! I know I promised our full itinerary during our stay at @iconacapemay !üíñOur arrival day was late so we just had time for dinner at The Blue Pig! The next day we had brunch at the Mad Batter, then went for a tour of the Physick estate! It was so fun and like a trip back in time. We then went to the Cape May Lighthouse & hung on the beach. Next we went to Washington Street Mall to check out the shops. Later on we had tickets to the holiday tree lighting ceremony (complete with a visit from Santa) at the Physick Estate. After that we had dinner at the Ugly Mug & then ended our night with a holiday lights trolley tour. The next morning we had brunch at Uncle Bills Pancake House! It was a short but fun-packed trip.üíñCape May is also now having breakfast with Santa, trolley rides with Mrs. Claus & other holiday fun. It‚Äôs a beautiful time to visit & I couldn‚Äôt say enough good things about @iconacapemay ! I shared some photos of our room as well as our picturesque morning view of the beach. I loved the vibe of our room & it was the perfect location too! We cannot wait to go back, literally will be counting the days to be reunited with Cape May & @iconacapemay .üíñHave you started getting into the holiday spirit yet? I cannot believe it‚Äôs December!üíñ

You‚Äôre a mean one Mr. Grinch ‚ù§Ô∏èüíöWe had such a fun weekend filled with holiday magic! Saturday we met friends for a fun dinner & then was hosted at the @grinchgrotto at @gsplaza ! My girls LOVE the Grinch & were SO excited to meet him! This is such a fun experience, but also really different because we always have Santa this time of year, but never saw an experience like this before!‚ù§Ô∏èüíöReservations are recommended & there are different packages to choose from! The Grinch also gives a sweet gift to each child! @gsplaza is also one of the best malls in NJ so you can absolutely make a fun day out of it! They also have a fun Kids Market for the holiday season, where children can shop for their loved ones & of course Santa experiences too!‚ù§Ô∏èüíöWe ended our weekend at Holiday in the Park at @sfgradventure & that was really fun too & beautifully decorated! I love seeing my girls enjoy all the holiday festivities. What are your favorite local activities to check out for the holiday season?!‚ù§Ô∏èüíöP.S. Did you watch the @undoinghbo finale?????üò¨

Let me introduce you to my all time favorite way to pimp my salads ü•ó This is what I call ‚Äûsavory granola‚Äú! It‚Äôs a crunchy and healthy way to add some nutrients as well as a nice taste to your salad. Prep in advance and bring it with you whenever your on the go!.Savory Granola Recipe.Ingredients:200g oats 100g pumpkin seeds 100g sunflower seeds 2 tablespoons sesame seeds100ml olive oil 3,5 tablespoons tomato paste 1 tablespoon maple syrup 3 tsp Dijon mustard 1 tsp paprika powder 1 teaspoon salt ¬Ω teaspoon Pepper.Instructions:Mix oats, pumpkin and sunflower seeds and sesame seeds in a big bowl.In a small bowl mix olive oil, tomato paste, maple syrup, mustard, paprika powder, salt and pepper until smooth. Add this mixture to the dry ingredients and mix well.Spread on a baking tray. Bake for about 15 minutes at 180 degrees, turn over and bake again for about 5-10 minutes.Take out and let cool down. Serve with your favorite salads..

When talking about health, many people think about a perfect body. But the outer shell does not always reflect how we really feel. Someone can be well-trained, but struggle with mental health. Or the opposite.Optimal physical health should above all support our general well-being. This includes exercise but also sufficient sleep and a nutritious diet. In the end, it is important to find the optimal balance between a healthy body, mental health and a vital spirit. Holistic health instead of an empty shell. That is what I am working on...

Remember that time I ran 13 miles without stopping and felt great about it? Yeah..me neither. LOL Today‚Äôs 4 miles were HORRIBLE. Like - the worst. My foot hurt. My leggings kept falling down (for the record, CRZ Yoga is great for lifting, apparently not so much for running). But I did it. And I used to enjoy it so maybe that means the next run will be better. Either way. Just passing the time until our @onepeloton comes.

I know the weekend is almost over, but treating your weekend just like your weekday is vital to seeing success. So many times in the past I would treat Friday-Sunday like a free for all. I worked hard M-F so I get to, right?! Wrong. When we do this, we undo all the hard work we did throughout the week, and that‚Äôs what causes the vicious cycle where we don‚Äôt see results, we get frustrated, and we try something else. Instead, do these five things EVERY SINGLE weekend and finally get past that wall:PLANOne of the best things you can do is head into your Friday with a plan for how you‚Äôre going to remain successful.For example, make sure your meal prep extends into the weekend so you‚Äôre not tempted to grab a sugary filler food instead of a nutritious meal. If you know that you‚Äôre going to eat out at a certain restaurant that weekend, research and decide ahead of time what you‚Äôre going to eat so that you‚Äôre not tempted last minute to make any poor choices in a moment of weakness.Take it a step further and plan your meals out by either writing them down, or logging them in an app (I like to use MyFitnessPal to help keep me on track). That way you can see ahead of time how you‚Äôre doing (if you happen to track your macros, calories, etc), and you‚Äôll feel more grounded as you move about your weekend. Knowing and seeing in advance what you‚Äôre going to eat for each meal will help you stick to it vs grabbing whatever looks good. Continued in comments

Smiling on the outside and the inside! üíô I want to talk about mental health today ‚Äî and the importance of caring about yourself.üíôMost of us try to project a happy exterior most of the time, regardless of how we‚Äôre truly feeling. We might actually not be happy at all, but we don‚Äôt want to show that and put on a smiling front ‚Äî even if we‚Äôre crying inside.üíôFor many years, I was depressed. My time living in New York and Pittsburgh was not the happiest or most fulfilling of my life. Because I have a very glass half full personality, I actually never even realized what a depressive weight had settled on my shoulders, until I moved to LA and started seeing a therapist. (Shoutout to @psych_today for having the BEST online tools for that.)üíôI‚Äôve always said that I feel like my therapist was handed to me on a silver platter. She came along at exactly the right time and had exactly the right things to say and the tools to help me not just manage my depression, but overcome it. She helped set me on a new course in life that helps me weather any storm that comes my way. This is not to say I‚Äôm always happy. I do actually frown once in awhile, even if you wouldn‚Äôt believe it by seeing my pics. But she helped me figure out how to work through my issues and approach life through an even happier, more positive lens than I had before.üíôI know that we all go through ups and downs in life. Sometimes the storm seems too great. Especially in this time of quarantine, it‚Äôs hard not to feel sad and overwhelmed and alone. üíôBut I‚Äôm here to tell you that you‚Äôre not alone. If you need a shoulder to cry on, a virtual hand to hold, or just a kind word, I‚Äôm here. Please DM me if you need that, or if you have questions about therapy, or how to find a therapist on Psychology Today. My DM door is always open.üíôI hope there will be something for you to smile about today.

Scar stories part 3: Twenty-one tiny scars on my forearm. One of the best things that came out of my triple bypass surgery was that the surgeon was able to take a biopsy from inside one of the arteries of my heart. It wasn't a guarantee he'd be able to get it, so when we found out he succeeded, it was big news! It was with that biopsy that my cardiologist found out that it wasn't plaque creating blockages in my heart. It was my own arteries causing the issues, the cells were proliferating and closing up on themselves.A group of brilliant doctors and researchers studied the biopsy of my artery and found that it had similar characteristics to cells found in my skin. So every year I get 3 little biopsies of my skin to track certain markers that give my doctor an indication of what's going on inside my arteries.I love these funny little scars on my arm. They're like tiny peepholes into my heart. ‚ô•Ô∏è
Room service, from a while back ü™ê

Scar stories part 2: Four more scars that I never knew I'd have after open heart surgery. The top two were from chest tubes to help drain my lungs and chest after surgery. The bottom two were from electrode wires that were connected to my heart to monitor it.When I came out of surgery, almost every part of my body was connected to something. But these four connections scared me the most. I wasn't expecting them, and it really freaked me out to look down and see tubes and wires coming out of my body. Eventually, I started to get used to them. And just as I was beginning to forget they were even there, it was time for them to come out - which scared me even more! I was beyond nervous for their removal.In the end, taking them out wasn't too bad. I didn't even need stitches. They just bandaged up the holes and told me they'd close back up on their own.And so, I was left with these four scars. I would say, after my chest scar, these are my favorite. They look cool, don't they? I love their symmetry ‚ö°Ô∏è

3 TIPS TO BECOMING MORE CONFIDENT IN WHO YOU ARE üëë‚Å£‚Å£1Ô∏è‚É£ ACCEPT & ALLOW ROOM FOR GROWTH. ‚Å£‚Å£Accept yourself just as you are because YES you are enough. If not, dismiss them- they don‚Äôt belong there. ‚Å£‚Å£3Ô∏è‚É£ BE MORE CHILD-LIKE‚Å£‚Å£This one seems silly, but it‚Äôs something I tapped into awhile ago & it‚Äôs one of my best kept secrets ü§´ Think back to when you were a child. Hey hey hey! I‚Äôve been a bit reflective lately and just wanted to share that life ruts happen (I feel like I‚Äôm just starting to get out of one after moving so much this summer and not working the last few months), and that‚Äôs okay! The last year or so I also felt sort of ‚Äústuck‚Äù in the routine of life I had and that I wasn‚Äôt doing much I was passionate about. Here‚Äôs your little reminder that sooner or later, you‚Äôll get out of that rut and will be doing something you love! For me, it was enrolling in the master esthiology program @avedainstituteprovo and working towards a career in esthetics. Ever since I was a teenager, I‚Äôve had a love for skincare and wanted to become an esthetician, but for whatever reason held myself back from going for it. I FINALLY did and really feel like I‚Äôm doing something I love and am passionate about! As someone who has mental health struggles, sometimes finding something that excites me can be hard, but I did it and you can, too! Just wanted to share this little message as inspiration and motivation to discover the things that excite you in life and chase after them! You can follow my esthetics page @aestheticsbylo for all things skincare! ü§ç, lauren

I think by now we all have heard of the amazing benefits of turmeric and ginger. They are both powerhouse foods that both have a myriad of benefits including decreased inflammation.My sister recently asked me for a recommendation on a turmeric supplement.  She was in excruciating pain from a herniated disc.  Her doctor recommended she take turmeric to help with the inflammatory pain.I suggested she try to take pure turmeric powder until dove in to find the most effective, pure, wholefood turmeric supplement. In my research I learned that most turmeric supplements only contain a single extract of curcumin and to unlock the benefits of turmeric you need a combination of black pepper, fat, and in liquid form.This knowledge lead me to find PRANA by @leefyorganics. PRANA was formulated by a holistic nutritionist to maximize the absorption of turmeric. The power of this elixir has helped people combat congestion, inflammatory pain, poor digestion, and many other ailments.With the current global pandemic and current events, our bodies are under a constant state of fight or flight. Chronic stress increases inflammation. Our modern lifestyle increases inflammation.So, why not take a wholefood(s) that is proven to reduce inflammation?  So, turmeric and ginger for dinner, everyday!!That would be ideal but not feasible for many of us, this is when I feel supplements are OK.  Especially ones made from wholefood.  The best part?? For many years I would attach my identity, happiness, and worthiness to my achievements and to my productivity. I wouldn‚Äôt give myself grace for resting and love myself for the fact of simply being and existing. If I wasn‚Äôt achieving, I wasn‚Äôt worthy.Here‚Äôs the thing, you can still work on goals, do what you love, and achieve. It‚Äôs just about appreciating and loving the process so you‚Äôre not waiting for those external things to bring you fulfillment. It‚Äôs about loving what is whether it‚Äôs low vibe or high vibe. That right there is unconditional love. That is an inside job.So love it all, love what is and still dream. We need your gifts in this world!

üó£ I don‚Äôt know who needs to hear this but, move through the discomfort!!This has been a mantra I‚Äôve had to remind myself all year.  The only way out is through even if it‚Äôs uncomfortable. Trust me, it‚Äôs easier said than being done. If you‚Äôve been paralyzed by fear lately, witness it, accept it, and forgive yourself. Action is the antidote to motivation and the trap of perfectionism. In my experience, when I wait for motivation to come to me, it never comes and nothing get‚Äôs done. To get through this I have to ground myself so that I avoid scrolling through social media, watching others for motivation, or watching TV to distract myself from realizing I‚Äôm self sabotaging.If you want to be courageous and move through the discomfort,  ground yourself and befriend the fear as courage does not exist without it.  Thank those voices for trying to protect you as a practice of unconditional love with yourself and take the next step within arms reach.Even if it‚Äôs baby steps, keep moving forward!Share or tag whoever needs to hear this message üåâ

One of the many things I loved about having our former salon, Peachy Keen Studio was the plethora of Boss Babes I got to meet and speak to on a daily basis. @erica_thomason , therapist and founder of @thedynamicchild and our feelings facilitator at @peachyality, is one of them. I met her over 6 years ago and love learning from her as we always bonded on self development and emotional intelligence. She is the one that introduced me to neuroscience. She introduced me to a¬†¬†@drjoedispenza video that literally impacted me to change the trajectory of my life. It woke me up to the fact that I‚Äôm really responsible for the way my life is and that I can change it to be more aligned with who I really am by going inward. Between my mentor, his teachings, learning from her and other friends, I‚Äôve learned so much about taking responsibility for my outer world. I‚Äôm always so fascinated with hearing Erica speak as she has a way of explaining things in a way that makes you feel that you can easily adopt these tools to live a more conscious life. Tonight for our Week 3¬†¬†Conscious Leadership lesson, she will be a guest speaker after I present the lesson.We will be talking: looking inward, understanding your triggers and using it for your personal growth, understanding your reactivity, emotional regulation and more.Because of our love of this topic, we decided to host a workshop in the beginning of the year to the public. Even if you‚Äôre not enrolled in the course, you can still purchase the webinar replay from tonight‚Äôs livestream. DM me for more info.

‚ÄúYour perspective decides whether you‚Äôre the victim or the victor of your life‚Äù- Shelsea The best way to change your perspective is to harvest the lessons out of your experiences. A question you can ask yourself when journaling is ‚ÄúWhat If I were to change my perspective ? What would that look like? ‚ÄúRadical responsibility is simple but it doesn‚Äôt mean it‚Äôs easy. If you can start taking responsibility, you can get out of being a victim. The moment we put blame on someone or something outside of ourselves, we are being victims.Where can you change your perspective and take responsibility so you free yourself from victim consciousness?

Indecision is a decision!I recently was asked to do a collaboration with a major company and turned it down. To be completely transparent, with having a start-up, the pay for the collaboration was extremely tempting. But another part of me knew that if I took that deal, it wasn‚Äôt going to be in complete integrity with myself and my audience.This offer wasn‚Äôt OUT of alignment with me, but I was hesitant and didn‚Äôt immediately accept it. I had to really think about this for an entire week, which was my first sign that I wasn‚Äôt truly on FIRE for this collaboration.If it‚Äôs not a hell yes, then it‚Äôs a no.Promote what you love, what‚Äôs in alignment with YOU, or what you would honestly be interested in learning more about. When you‚Äôre faced with anything in life, have integrity with yourself FIRST.Don‚Äôt be a sell out.Happiness and doing what lights you up is ALWAYS more important than any dollar amount. Every time you stay true to you, you create space for more, and most times BETTER opportunities to come along. To my ‚Äúinfluencer‚Äù friends: If it doesn‚Äôt feel natural, don‚Äôt do it. If you‚Äôre undecided, you‚Äôve decided. Instead of trying to figure out how you can make a post work for you (because remember you ARE the brand,) just say no.In practicing self-trust and knowing that better opportunities will present themselves we can start seeing more authenticity online.

Aligned is the new hustle.Destroy the idea that you have to be constantly working or grinding in order to be successful. Remember to enjoy it. Embrace the concept that rest, recovery, and reflection are essential parts of the progress towards a successful and ultimate happy life.In the past, I would cause myself unnecessary anxiety and run myself ragged and didn't simply BE. If you've been feeling anxious, slow down and ground. If you've been feeling tired, rest. This is your body‚Äôs way of telling you, it's your red flag. Simply listen and do what you gotta do to take care of you. Instead of depleting yourself over and over, remind yourself - Deplete, Replenish and repeat.¬†¬†Check in with yourself like you would with a best friend and give yourself the love you need.Are you aligned? Tag your friends that believe in doing life this way!!

column3: #Ticketmaster is under fire for changing the wording in its refund policy during the #pandemic.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†ÄInitially, their policy said that if a show is postponed or rescheduled, you could either use that ticket for the new date or get a full refund.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†ÄBut now the site says you‚Äôll only get your money back if a show is canceled.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†ÄThis wouldn‚Äôt be a problem if most of the concerts and events were canceled; however, artists and venues have consistently been postponing shows to a future date.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†ÄAccording to Ticketmaster‚Äôs website, ‚ÄúIf you see a ‚ÄòRequest a Refund‚Äô link under Self Service, you are good to go.‚Äù‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†ÄBut they mostly leave that decision to the event organizers, writing, ‚ÄúIf your event has been rescheduled and the event's organizer is offering refunds, this option will be visible under the event in your Ticketmaster account.‚Äù‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†ÄIn a statement to USA Today, Ticketmaster said that its policy on postponed events hasn‚Äôt changed but said the wording on its website was edited for clarity.

Bar the ‚Äúold C√©line‚Äù pendant (which I still love despite its ubiquity‚Äîa sign of something right for your personal style) I do try to source new, long-lasting jewellery pieces from independent brands with a unique aesthetic. ‚Ä¢ Alona Shelemy of @byalona came to my attention via a fabulous collaboration with @bettinalooney a few seasons back. Even with more natural forms like this shell and faux pearl necklace from the main line you can sense a bit of ‚Äò80s gaudiness‚Äîsomething I like very much. ‚Ä¢ @pascalejamesjewellery is a London-based jewellery label with sustainability and craftsmanship at the fore. I first found design duo and couple Antonia Pascale and Christopher James when they started casting lemon slices to create these incredible moulds for gold earrings. I wear these on repeat because they bring all the classicism of gold hoops but with extra pizzaz. There‚Äôs much more to their collections now (including a bespoke service) but I know these will have a place in my collection forever. ‚Ä¢ @_anni_lu_ became popular in the UK a few years ago for these organic-looking pearl earrings and the matching bracelets, necklaces and anklets. Baroque meets ‚Äò90s tween, designer Helle Vestergaard Poulsen‚Äôs delicate pieces have a playfulness to them‚Äîsee the little red gemstone dots and shell studs?

@flora.roberts paints beautiful flowers. And those bows! Lovely.
Probably going to put the heating on.

Call me Kirsty Bloody Allsopp, I‚Äôve only gone and made some cushions! I bought this @libertylondon fabric a year ago and then, well, things got busy. I didn‚Äôt have quite enough fabric (could only afford 1.5m) so it‚Äôs a slightly botched job at the back but they do make this vintage rattan swivel chair‚Äîand the room‚Äîlook a little bit more complete. Now if only I had the chance to sit here, read a book and actually finish a cup of tea‚ÄîLOL dream on.

The last time I left the house in a short dress was about 18 years ago on a very gross-but-ridiculously-fun post-GCSEs holiday in Malia. It was a ‚Äò60s floral halterneck that had been shortened up to here and I wore it with clear PVC heels from Dune‚Äîfelt quite bold for someone whose knees generally never see the light of day. So perhaps it‚Äôs not a coincidence that another mod-style number has finally talked me into the idea almost two decades later... but let‚Äôs hope I can act like a bit more of a grown up whilst wearing this one. *Gifts tagged.

On March 13th I packed a carry on bag thinking I‚Äôd be gone for a week or two tops. Little did I know corona had other plans and I‚Äôd actually be away from LA for 5 months. Life just literally took its course and as the world seemed to be getting crazier day by day somehow I genuinely felt like everything was going to be ok at the same time. While the lingering fear of the unknown crept up so did the solace of our new normal. the juxtaposition of this whole mess made me feel guilty at times (still does sometimes) because while so many people were being affected negatively I felt like I was thriving. 5 months ago my relationship of over a year was a secret bc we were worried that our full time jobs and our careers would be on the line. 2020 has been the craziest fucking year ever but it‚Äôs been one of full clarity. A 2020 vision. It‚Äôs opened my eyes to what really matters and what doesn‚Äôt.  Although the virus is a VERY real thing and we can‚Äôt forget it, every day that passes is one deeper into our new normal. We‚Äôre in it now, and we‚Äôre living it now. Don‚Äôt be scared, embrace it. I‚Äôd be lying to you if I didn‚Äôt have some down time throughout this mess but you know what: there‚Äôs always a silver lining! Everything happens for a reason and I hope everyone stays as healthy as possible for as long as they can. Sooner or later it might strike us but in the meantime let‚Äôs remain as responsible as we can. I just got back to LA and have been laying low for a minute to avoid seeing people but my tests just came back Negative. God bless. üôèüèº

This is my uncle and PRS Awarded Music Composer Stelios Pissis. I owe it ALL to him. My love for music and singing. Today he writes "17 years of being confined in this room and in this bed, with respiratory support. Who complains about the new Covid-19 isolation measures? Let's wear our masks and say 'Glory be to You, God'." Stelios has had Muscular Dystrophy at progressing stages ever since he was 6 years old. He went from being in a wheelchair to having to be confined to a bed as the condition progressed, 17 years ago. A few years back, he was able to compose using one finger that he could still move and a trackpad on Cubase (Digital Audio Workstation) on his computer. In the last three years he lost that ability, and now he's composing with the power of technology and his eyes with a tracking system that lets him operate his computer. He has composed music that has been played by the Symphonic Orchestra of Kremlin and national stars, ensembles and choirs across the world, including composing the music for a TV Series in Cyprus. It is some of the most beautiful music I have ever heard. I would urge you to go on YouTube and watch the documentary dedicated to him, you can find it by typing Stelios Pissis on YouTube.Stelio, you are the strength and inspiration for my sisters, my family and I and all people who know you. Your light is the brightest fire I have ever encountered. I love you I love you I love you

A sneaky little way to keep yourself from failing.You‚Äôre not confused, not really. You‚Äôre scared, and it‚Äôs okay to feel scared. Honestly, it is. What‚Äôs not okay is using fear as an excuse to shift responsibility away from yourself, as an excuse to not take action.Tell yourself the truth, you know enough to get started, and you can figure the rest out on the way.

Cole‚Äôs hard work transitioning into his career in the medical field + my unwavering dedication to my @monatofficial business is what got us here at 23 & 26 years old. If I hadn‚Äôt been brave enough to say yes to starting an online business my senior year of college, if I‚Äôd followed the norm and gone into a job in my degree field, we‚Äôd still be living in the basement. There‚Äôd be no home, no dream wedding on the way (whenever COVID decides to chill), nothing even remotely close to what we‚Äôve built in these two short years.When we started dating in high school we used to day dream about our first home. Imagine someone travelled back from the future and confirmed you achieved all your goals. You wouldn‚Äôt feel disheartened, you wouldn‚Äôt give into your fears, and you wouldn‚Äôt give up - no matter what happened.That‚Äôs exactly how you need to act. Act as if you‚Äôve been assured that your success is inevitable, and it will be. Act as if it‚Äôs certain, and it will be.

Don‚Äôt be fooled. Holding yourself back so you can avoid failure IS failing. Keeping your goals small so you can can avoid disappointment IS disappointing. By standing still, by being too afraid to push yourself, you‚Äôre creating exactly what you don‚Äôt want.

Some things take insane bravery, but after that, you‚Äôll be free.You might be terrified to your very core, but make sure you do it anyways. I promise you, those moments of courage are what change your life. They open doors. They push you forward into something more than what was before.

Your dreams will choose you, but you have to start. You have to choose them first. When you decide to show up, nothing can keep you from what you are destined for. Not the pandemic. Not the economy. Not another global event. Not a bad year. You do not have to be defined by all the obstacles, instead let yourself define how you overcome them.We‚Äôve heard it over and over again, this has been an unprecedented year... so why can‚Äôt you have unprecedented success from this point on?Maybe it seems unrealistic to the outside world, but you knew it was coming. You knew it was coming, because you decided who you were meant to be.Only you can make 2021 your best year yet. Only you can decide that you will NOT wait one more minute, one more day, one more month, one more year to build the life you know you deserve. The life you were made for. It‚Äôs already yours... you just have to DECIDE, and get started.Happy December ‚ú® it‚Äôs time to claim your blessings

Can we talk about how important what we are feeding into our mind?So Evie-Mae had hair cut last week. She doesn't like to cut her frindge short  but the hairdresser cut it shorter than normal... The next day, she woke up and the first thing she told me was if she really have to go to school..I asked her why. Her response was that she quite nervous what her friends will think of her new hair and she think it doesn't suit her.She had a bit of emotional moment. I gave her a big hug and told her that its all in her mind.On the way to school, we talked about what we are feeding into our mind. If we feed positive, happy thoughts which will make us happier in life. Its good to have other people opinions but the most important is how you feel about yourself.It starts with what you are feeding into your own mind. Negative thoughts and fear would only make you feel weaker.Your mind is very powerful. The moment you start filling with postive thoughts, great things can happen. What a whirlwind of a year it has been. A year since I tucked all of my dreams into an airplane ticket, en route to destinations still unknown. A year of crossing oceans and living out of suitcases. A year of moments that have turned into valuable memories. A year of living what life has always encapsulated for me: infinite possibility.2019 has been the year that came with a gentle tap on my shoulder, reminding me of who I was and all that I could be, if only I‚Äôd just open my arms and let the light in, stopped overthinking and started living. It‚Äôs been the year for unlearning. For stripping away the work I didn‚Äôt thrive doing, the relationships I have outgrown and limiting ideas I‚Äôve been leaning on to guide me. I made room for my actual life to begin. It‚Äôs been a busy time.. of change, of progress, of tiny beginnings. I am rather mystified as to how the year managed to slip by so quickly..so suddenly, but here we are, on the bring of a new decade.. and I am thinking of all the beautiful things that are contained within my life‚Ä¶ what it is to be alive.
what dreams are made of.
two souls.

Just over a month ago I had a vision and from that exact moment, that vision turned into a mission. Fashion Revolution Week was an absolute success. Overwhelmed about the support we‚Äôve received from brands, people and places during the past weeks.
made it part of my job to look at all aspects of the industry - including where our clothing lands after we don‚Äôt want it anymore.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs being here now that‚Äôs important. There‚Äôs no past and there‚Äôs no future. Time is a very misleading thing. All there is ever, is the now. We can gain experience from the past, but we can‚Äôt relive it; and we can hope for the future, but we don‚Äôt know if there is one.‚Äù‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäGeorge Harrison

waiting for you, Paul.

column2: Moms wear an invisible crown of bravery. Within the walls of our home & in our littles hearts, we are inspired to be kindred brave. We had a group play date the other day & it was so refreshing to hear the triumphs and challenges from all the other mamas. All different in their own ways, but a mutual understanding as a fellow mom. Motherhood is hard. Loving my baby and being his mama is not! That‚Äôs the easy part!

Sometimes things fall out of place, so that something better can fall in! I‚Äôve been working on finding clinical placement for my final semester as an NNP student & what I initially prayed for didn‚Äôt work out, but what I will be doing now is EVEN BETTER! I was so anxious and worried through the process, bummed when it wasn‚Äôt what I expected and then literally prayed about it and FIVE MINUTES LATER a dream came true! Immediate weight lifted. Contentment. Grateful. Not surprised. This is just a reminder to myself yet again...that when I try to put too much control into earthly things, God steps in and does it better! Worry, fear & anxiety is assuming he doesn‚Äôt know what he‚Äôs doing...&&&& girl, that just isn‚Äôt true! His perfect timing in the cutest Fall inspired outfits from @kittsona

WELCOME TO MY ZEN DEN.A positive + quiet space focused on meditation, mindfulness, inner-health, anti-aging + wellness. We‚Äôll be offering:.- infrared sauna- red light therapy- meditations- events- retail (you can now shop my morning routine IRL Y'ALL).Here‚Äôs the deal. I created my Zen Den in an extra guest room I had in my little Hudson Valley home, Villa Gilleo about 4 years ago. I retreat to this space every morning + in some evenings. I needed to make myself a little sanctuary area that I could focus on my mindfulness + wellbeing after going through major trauma.. I needed to heal. I found that since I made the commitment to daily meditation, breath work, red light therapy, + my overall health, wellness, immune system, energy, skin, + happiness began to improve..Over the course of the past few years my Instagram community slowly continued to grow. So many of you been asking about my daily rituals, morning routines, wellness practices, how to meditate, how to feel happier, + a lot of you said you didn‚Äôt have the space in your home for a ‚Äúzen den‚Äù or a quiet space to have moments of healing+peace. And then there were a lot of my tribe that couldn‚Äôt afford to buy a red light because, welp, they ain't cheap hunni!.After the shit show of 2020, I needed a new project. Makeup was cancelled for half the year and it made me question a lot. I‚Äôm so used to being busy + for work to completely stop, made me spiral a bit. On top of it I suffered from a MAJOR heartbreak, and just like you, the panic of the unknown, COVID, crazy political events happening in the world, the media, protests, + much more anxiety filled SHIT yet so many of you were reaching out to little ol ME for advice + help.The one thing that remained consistent was my daily practices. Through my practices + rituals I began to heal again. + what helped me the most was my community, my friends + support systems. We came together in My Zen Den @ Villa Gilleo to talk, dig deep, red light, do breath work, make vision boards, move our bodies, meditate, etc. Then I thought HOW CAN I BRING MY ZEN DEN TO THE COMMUNITY?.You‚Äôve been asking for years + I‚Äôve been listening üëáüèºCONTINUED IN COMMENTSüëáüèº

column2: Don‚Äôt look back on the past, we‚Äôre not going that way, you are NOT your past, you are NOT your old stories, you‚Äôre the narrator, don‚Äôt like where you‚Äôre at? Then rewrite that shit.Back on the East coast for a little bit.. WE GOT A BUSINESS TO LAUNCH FOR THE COMMUNITY HUNNI üöÄ ARE YOU READY BEACON?!.+ of course your Monday Quick reminders:.- be selective of the books your reading, the accounts your following on social, the podcasts and conversations you‚Äôre listening to, the television and movies you‚Äôre watching, we become what we consume. Make sure it‚Äôs positive, informative, maybe throw in some humor + entertainment in there, but be selective to help guide you to the best version of your highest self.- Now is the time of year you want to turn the humidifiers on before bed to keep that skin right and tight, might as well get yourself an air purifier too.. make sure the water is purified.- when it starts getting colder I switch my PM moisturizer over to a thicker one, i really love @paulaschoice intensive repair cream with retinol at night, still wear your spf during the day.- the colder it gets, try to avoid super hot showers for long periods of time, it will dry the shit out of your skin... i use coconut oil or jojoba oil for my body afterwards.Love is all there is. All the glitz and glam of materialist shit feels good for a hot sec, but the love you find in friendships, relationships, family, etc. that‚Äôs what matters at the end of the day. Don‚Äôt loose sight of that..- we are supposed to have belly fat. It‚Äôs there to protect your organs, it‚Äôs natural, stop stressing yourself out over it. Love your body.I wish everyone an amazing week. LETS FUCKING GET IT! x.

COMMUNITY IS IMMUNITY.First, this is @clinttorres_hair we hustle together from MIAMI ‚úàÔ∏è to LA, he does üí£ hair, has the best fckn energy and vibe ‚ö°Ô∏èso go check him out HUNNIIII...Second, I‚Äôve met so many incredible people the last few weeks and have bonded + connected with, have had deep heart to heart conversations, shared incredible stories, danced, laughed + cried with, and I just want to remind you that people are good. Rich people, poor people, homeless people, athletic people, creative people, artistic people... Everyone has a story. Listen to others. Relate to others. Let go of judgments. There‚Äôs no such thing as competition when there is collaboration, connection, + community. Stop gossiping. Let‚Äôs get real. SOCIAL CONNECTION MAY BE THE MOST IMPORTANT HEALTH INTERVENTION..It absolutely fckn matters that we come together. Hug, touch, smile, cry, dance, laugh, feel for each other. Have an open mind and an open heart. The people I connect with know what I‚Äôm talking about. I love all you people, people of all religions, beliefs, ages, sizes, colors... we all want peace, love, and happiness. Now is a time to connect and heal. You all inspire me I LOVE YOU üíïüíïüíï..

A few months ago, I wrote a blog post on Emetophobia and Anxiety. I‚Äôll link the post in my bio for those of you who are new to my page or who haven‚Äôt heard of it! Alike many other fears and disorders derived from anxiety,this fear launches an attack on me nearly every single Winter. This Winter being one of the strangest ones, with everything going on. Initially, I was confident that I wouldn‚Äôt catch a stomach bug, knowing that everyone is taking extra caution. But over the last few weeks, I‚Äôve noticed the fear begin to shadow my every move. I was in town on Saturday and was deeply triggered after using the public loo‚Äôs (someone had been unwell). I realised that maybe I‚Äôm not safe, maybe I should be worried, and maybe there is a possibility of catching something. So off I went into my shell, terrified of the unknown. Those with Emetophobia are terrified of transferring germs into their mouth, we‚Äôre more inclined to be extra weary when it comes to hand washing (just saying I was a Queen hand washer pre covid.) üòõJust yesterday, I left the supermarket and while in a conversation, noticed I was biting my nail, as you do. I was instantly triggered and since this moment, have lost an appetite to eat a big meal (in case I‚Äôm sick) and have been consciously making an even greater effort to wash my hands every hour. Covid scares most people, but getting sick scares me more. Those with OCD carry similar traits, they may feel the need to wash their hands a certain amount of times. One of my quirks is I come home every day and sanitise my phone. Something very few people think to do. My point is, this fear is rooted inside of me, but half of you don‚Äôt see it. I don‚Äôt broadcast my worries. I don‚Äôt tell you how many times I‚Äôve looked for reassurance from a friend or family member that I definitely won‚Äôt catch a bug. Every single person has little quirks and fears, just like me. But we choose to internalise our worries in case we are misjudged. Let‚Äôs break that stigma. There are thousands of people just like me, and by vocalising it and blogging about it, I discovered hundreds of like minded men and women. ‚ú® Now can everyone please wash your hands. x

column3: #WorldChildrensDay ‚ù§Ô∏è I was a very lucky child. Like many others, I had a roof over my head, supportive parents and a childhood I can call memorable. Unfortunately, a lot of children do not live in similar circumstances, and in the midst of a pandemic, they are struggling greatly. With Christmas nearing, we as a nation can help young children in uncomfortable living situations by doing our bit. This year, I‚Äôm going to be donating to The Irish Youth Foundation, who have developed programmes to aid children in need of a better education and livelihood. I will also be donating to the ISPCC, who provide a safe network for children via Childline. Their job is to listen to young children and adolescents, and provide them with therapeutic support. These are two phenomenal foundations. Please donate what you can. ü§çüíõ Spread the word and nominate your friends to join in and get posting a silly or sweet photo of you as a child! üíï #IYF #ISPCC #MakeADifference #GenerationPandemic https://www.ispcc.ie/https://www.iyf.ie/Those nominated are tagged! üíï

column3: #StoryTime - Spent the last 5 days spiritually reconnecting to a country i knew nothing about ‚ú® For those that don‚Äôt know, my father is Dominican and my mother is Ecuadorian. I grew up with my mother and by default always considered myself more Ecuadorian. The food, traditions, music, and travels to the homeland made me feel a deep love for the Ecuadorian culture. But i never really felt that same love and passion for Dominican Republic. I learned more about my Dominican roots when I entered high school. But still, there was never a sense of pride or a spark of solidarity.I returned from this trip with a DEEP appreciation for my father‚Äôs country and the rich & beautiful culture I am so incredibly blessed to be a part of üá©üá¥‚ú®‚ù§Ô∏èScreaming a THANK YOU to @ahcheee for giving me an experience of a lifetime üòò#suzzstravels #travellatina #naturallycurly #travelblogger #r29somos #latinxstories #spiritualawakenibg #wellnessjourney #latinaswhotravel #cabrera #dominicanbloggers

column2: Black Friday shopping is undeniably the biggest sale of the year. A little bit of planning and being mindful while shopping will help make the best of holiday sales. Here are 3 things I personally do before I shop on Black Friday sales:1. List down the items that you absolutely need  Writing down helps to clear your mind and also helps with determining if this is something you need or you want it just because you saw it on Instagram or on sale.2. Add Items to your shopping cart before the sale   Unlike usual Black Friday shopping where you will have to stay in line for door-busters, It‚Äôll be mostly online this year. This gives you an opportunity to plan the shopping better and add the items you absolutely need to your cart beforehand. 3. Consider Shopping from small and local businesses  Shopping small is an amazing way to encourage new ideas and giving back to the community. Studies have shown that small businesses contribute to 2 out of 3 new jobs here in the United States. By choosing to spend money on small businesses, you‚Äôresimultaneously contributing to, and benefitting from it. The small business owner will likely go that extra mile to make you happy which you wont get to experience from big retailers.Check out the blog post for more on this topic. Link is in my bio.

column2: Happy Sunday everyone!!As Dstylebook has grown and it's been a while I did my introduction, I'll take this opportunity to do an intro and share some not so random facts about meMy name is Divya, born and raised in the outskirts of Chennai, India and moved to United States in 2013 after marriage. Currently living in New Jersey with my husband @sriramssg and my 19 month old, Kyra. I started Dstylebook in 2015 as a page to document my style journey. A lot of changes happened since then and 2019 is when I found out the topics that I'm passionate to talk about in this platform - sustainable fashion, restyling and recycling, mindful consumerism and ofcourse sareeingNow some not so random facts about me:(Thanks for the tag @desigal1010 )1. Work hard, chill harder is my life motto2. I'm a linguaphile, love learning new languages3. I'm a big foodie. I love trying new foods but when there‚Äôs biryani on the table, every other dish just fades away from my sight4. I was never a chai or coffee person but this year I found myself becoming more of a coffee person, need coffee in the morning (may be parenting is doing that to meüòÇ)5. Reading a book first thing in the morning and last thing before bed is what I call a perfect day6. Classic and simple are two words I use to describe my style7. Queen of overplanning and procrastinating üòÇüòÇ8. Use it until it screams 'I'm done' is like my thing. Throwing away doesn't come naturally to me.

Day 2! Of course i am extremely grateful for not only the love of my life but my daughter‚Äôs father. I knew without a doubt Tyler would be an amazing dad the day Logan was born. I had just delivered her and we found out she had a fever and wasn‚Äôt breathing well. I carried and grew her for 9 months and 20 minutes after she was born, they were going to take her to the nursery to get more tests and oxygen. I couldn‚Äôt go with my baby. I was crushed that i didn‚Äôt get more time to love on this little life that i had grown a relationship with while she was in my tummy. The only person that could go with her was Ty. I can‚Äôt explain the love i had for Tyler in that moment when he assured he wouldn‚Äôt leave her side. I was heart broken that i couldn‚Äôt go with her but knowing that her dad was right by her, watching over everything, made me feel such peace. Tyler stood right next to Logan‚Äôs bedside for over 4 hours. As my sisters were relaying info from Tyler to me, she went to look through the nursery window. She came back in my room and started to tell me how Logan was doing and told me that Tyler hasn‚Äôt even looked away from her.. not even for a second. We both started to cry. As women, you carry these babies and KNOW them for 9 months. My sister and I both knew that Tyler isn‚Äôt exactly a ‚Äúbaby person.‚Äù He hasn‚Äôt been around newborns very much and frankly, i didn‚Äôt know how comfortable he would be those first few days. When my sister told me how Tyler was protecting our daughter, i was overwhelmed with gratitude for him. He knew that it was killing me to not be with her. We were all so sad that Logan was being poked and was sick.. but Tyler stepped up and jumped right into his role as a father. It was in that first day of Logan‚Äôs life that i felt us come together as parents. Tyler slept by Logan‚Äôs bedside that night. He talked to all of the doctors. He was amazing. I am so lucky to get to have him as a partner. He‚Äôs the dad i dreamt of for my future kids. I‚Äôll never forget how he is tackled his new role as a father and gave me such peace, knowing our daughter was safe with her dad. ‚ù§Ô∏è Love you ty, I‚Äôll always be grateful for you.
My sisters. My family. My parents. So grateful for them. They are my best friends. ‚ù§Ô∏è @russellmnelson challenged us to post everyday for 7 days, sharing what you are grateful for! ‚ù§Ô∏è

Sharing something that I‚Äôve been doing the past 8 months (AKA Logan‚Äôs entire life ü§™) that has really helped my productivity, how my home feels and less overwhelm. ‚ÄúWhat do i call this magical thing?‚Äù You May ask.. it‚Äôs called my TO-DO LIST BASKET. It‚Äôs genius.I promise you‚Äôll wanna try it.You need a decent size collapsible basket! (I have some linked in my bio!) Set your basket in a high traffic area of your home. When you walk in the door and don‚Äôt have time to hang up your jacket in the closet? Put it in the basket. Brought a pack of diapers in from the car but don‚Äôt have time to go put them away? Put it in the basket.What about your child‚Äôs toy that‚Äôs on the floor? Put it in the basket. Part of your Halloween costume still sitting on the kitchen counter?Put it in the basket. You get the idea right? Place all of the random crap üòÖ in this basket. It keeps it contained and makes your house feel less messy! It‚Äôs your catch all basket! NOW.. the important part.. Set aside 10-20 minutes to tackle that TO-DO LIST basket every single day. This is crucial. If you don‚Äôt do this, it will soon become a big ol‚Äô mess and overwhelm you even more. Every night after Logan goes to bed and before i get comfy and start to wind down, i bust out my basket. I walk around with it and start putting it all away. Keep in mind this concept has been around for a long time.. but the second i started seeing it as a ‚Äúto-do list‚Äù the second it changed how i tidy! Don‚Äôt think of it as a DUMPING GROUND. Think of this basket as a list of to-dos that you have to get done before you go to bed. You can even add post it notes in there of reminders that you can do while you are walking around, emptying the basket. Say it with me.. No more random clutter! No more random clutter! No more random clutter! üíÉüèºGIVEAWAY üö®: i want to give away a set of my favorite collapsible baskets! I‚Äôll pick one winner Tuesday at 8PM MST. To enter simply like this post, make sure to follow me and tag a friend in the comments! ‚ù§Ô∏è

column3: #GivingTuesday everyone!!!! I ask that you donate what you'd spend on a soda to @savinggraceepilepsyfdn.üíúOur mission is to help people with epilepsy live normal & independent lives. To learn more or to donate go to: www.sgepilepsyfdn.org/donate

column2: EPILEPSY//Looking back at this
column3: #EpilepsyAwarenessMonth in pure admiration. Raising Awareness for Epilepsy is a passion. My epilepsy journey started over 20 years ago. I'm thankful for the good & the bad. It's all my story. When I decided to share my epilepsy journey,  I did it because I really needed to figure out what epilepsy meant to me.  Epilepsy didn't define me. However, I never thought I'd be on this advocacy journey. But I am.  I'm happy to have met some amazing people along the way.üíú‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢There are so many stigmas attached to epilepsy. It is considered an invisible illness, some people think its funny, while others simply don't understand it... One seizure can have you in recovery for hours or days.  When a seizure occurs, the person isn't in control anymore. That is a scary thing. I call it "loss time." Imagine waking up and you don't know what happened- you don't even remember falling asleep! That's sorta how epilepsy can be.‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢So as you guys know, I recently started Saving Grace Epilepsy Foundation @savinggraceepilepsyfdn - which will help people with epilepsy live a normal life by helping with:‚óãJob Placement ‚óãMedication ‚óãTransportation ‚óãSeizure Safety ‚óãCombat job discrimination So on #GivingTuesday think about us!‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢#epilepsyawarness #epilepsyawarenessmonthüíú #epilepsyadvocate #epilepsystrong #invisableillness #epilepsyadvocates #seizuresafety
